---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Gaia Sausage-Enceladus (GSE)";
import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Gaia Sausage-Enceladus (GSE)</h1>

    <p>
      The <strong>Gaia Sausage-Enceladus (GSE)</strong> is a major accreted dwarf galaxy component of the Milky Way's stellar halo. It was discovered through Gaia astrometry as a distinct kinematic population of stars on highly radial orbits (~10 Gyr ago). The GSE defines much of the MW's inner halo and has an extremely high velocity anisotropy (β ≈ 0.9).
    </p>

    <h2>Key properties</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Progenitor mass: ~(1–3) × 10^8 M_☉</li>
      <li>Merger time: ~10 Gyr ago</li>
      <li>Velocity anisotropy: β ≈ 0.9 (highly radial orbits)</li>
      <li>Current location: dominates inner halo (6–25 kpc)</li>
      <li>Distinctive features: tilted triaxial distribution; associated with Virgo Overdensity and Hercules-Aquila Cloud</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>LMC effects on GSE structure</h2>
    <p>
      Dillamore et al. (2026) show that the LMC's tidal perturbations can reshape and tilt initially axisymmetric haloes, preferentially affecting the highly eccentric GSE orbits. This suggests that the observed tilt and overdensities (HAC/VOD) may arise from ongoing LMC perturbations rather than pristine merger geometry<sup><a href="/pages/dillamore_2026_gse_lmc">1</a></sup>.
    </p>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Dillamore A. M., Sanders J. L., Brooks R. A. N. (2026). arXiv:2603.11159.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
